We recommended that the department heads concerned:

At the beginning of the year, submit to the Municipal Mayor a list of all ongoing government PPAs and those that are to be implemented during the year;
Within ten (10) days after the award of the infrastructure project or before the start of the program/activity, community, communicate to the Municipal Mayor that the appropriate project signboards and/or public notices are already posted;
Submit to the Municipal Mayor, Quarterly Report on Government Projects/Programs/Activities at last day of the end of the quarter, supported with pictures of tarpaulin and the PPAs.

Further, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor designate a staff of the Mayor’s Office to consolidate the reports mentioned in Sections 1.7.1 and 1.7.3 submitted by various department heads, and submit the same to the Audit Team, within the reglementary period.

Moreover, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor inform the Audit Team within ten (10) days after the award of the infrastructure project or before the start of the program/activity, that the appropriate project signboards and/or public notices are already posted, based on the submitted report of the department heads concerned.

We recommended that MDRRMO: 

a.) provide for the lacking supporting documents needed to substantiate the release and distribution of welfare goods such as, but not limited to, duly signed Distribution Sheets, Incident Reports and the like;
b.) indicate the reason and basis for the release of the welfare goods in the supporting documents;
c.) submit monthly and on time the RSMI together with its supporting documents to the Accounting department;
d.) together with the inventory team, facilitate the conduct of semi-annual physical count of all inventories on hand in the MDRRM office; and
e.) assign personnel who will regularly and promptly monitor the purchases and releases of goods (charged from GF and STF) held in the MDRRM office.

We recommended that the Municipal Health Officer;
submit to the Audit team the lacking distribution list enumerated in Table;

prepare and properly accomplish the RSMI ever 10th day of the month, duly supported with the RIS, Distribution Lists and other supporting documents; and

submit RSMI together with RIS, Distribution Lists and other supporting documents to the Municipal Accountant not later than 15th day of the month

We recommended that the MDRRMO.

Prepared a detailed breakdown of the unaccounted relief goods showing the recipient Barangays, name and position of the official who received the goods for distribution, date , issued, kind and quantity of goods and other necessary information;

Immediately prepare and send demand letters to said barangays compelling them to submit proof of distribution for the relief goods;

Prepare and submit to COA a detailed breakdown of goods procured for STS Odette relief efforts which were used for STS Paeng instead;

Moving forward, monitor the Barangay’s schedule of relief goods distribution and assign an MDRRMO staff to collect the distribution sheets immediately after the activity;

Monitor the movement of goods, the status of their distribution and the completeness of the necessary supporting documents; and

Submit to the Municipal Accountant the RSMI, RIS and proof of distribution not later than the 15th day of the month after the distribution of goods.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Direct the personnel-in-charge to renew the registration of the five (5) serviceable vehicles and expedite the registration of four (4) new vehicles operating without LTO registration.

Instruct the Custodian or Driver of the Motor Vehicle to stop the operation of the vehicle with expired LTO registration.

Consider the provision of an adequate garage or shed to house all motor vehicles, including those for disposal.

We also recommended that the personnel-in-charge and the Property Custodian:

Exhaust all possible means to locate the records of registration not presented during audit;
Keep the records of registration for all LGU vehicles, monitor their expiry dates and schedule the annual renewal of LTO registration in coordination with the Property Custodian or Driver of the Motor Vehicle;
Schedule for repair inactive vehicles which can still be repaired within reasonable cost;

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the assigned personnel to:

C. Extract from the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment, as well as from the Report on the Physical Count of Inventories, prepared in accordance with the prevailing guidelines, the data for the PIF pertaining to the insurable assets and interest of the government (excluding impaired properties for disposal and other unqualified properties);

D. Gather other necessary data on these properties;

E. Cause the appraisal of the insurable properties and other assets of the LGU.  For this purpose, an in-house appraisal shall be sufficient if the property or insurable interest has a value of ₱10 million and below.  Otherwise, an independent appraisal shall be necessary;

F. Submit the consolidated PIF to the Audit Team and the GIF, GSIS, not later than April 30 of each year; and

Moreover, we recommended that the assigned personnel coordinate with the Inventory Team, Municipal Engineer, Municipal Assessor and Municipal Accountant in identifying the buildings owned by the Municipality on records and in actual count.

