We recommended that the Disposal Committee, in coordination with the Bids and Awards Committee, submit a written explanation to the Audit Team on the reasons why the previous disposal proceedings did not materialize in Calendar Year (CY) 2024;
We also recommended that the Property Officer, under the supervision of the newly-appointed General Services Officer, immediately prepare and submit the updated Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) to the Appraisal and Disposal Committee, copy furnished to the Audit Team;
Furthermore, we recommended that the Appraisal and Disposal Committee, in coordination with the concerned officers and employees, promptly prepare and submit the necessary documents to facilitate the appraisal and disposal of unserviceable properties, and expedite the disposal process in strict compliance with applicable rules and regulations;
Moreover, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor, Municipal Accountant, and Property Custodian evaluate the list of non-existing/missing PPEs prepared by the Inventory Team, and initiate the appropriate disposition procedures for said properties; and
Lastly, we recommended that the Municipal Accountant, Property Custodian, General Services Officer, and Inventory Committee exhaust all available means to review and reconcile records in order to identify the unidentified PPEs. If, after all efforts have been exerted, the assets remain unidentifiable, the same should be applied for derecognition through the one-time cleansing of accounts in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

